    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-07-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-07-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="354"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d354">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">320/7–2954</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Telephone Conversation, by the Acting Assistant
                        Secretary of State for United Nations Affairs</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_WAINHOUSEDW1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wainhouse</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-07-29">July 29,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <item>Subject:</item>
                    <item>Ninth General Assembly Presidency.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_SARASINP1">Sarasin</persName> telephoned me this
                    morning to say that <persName corresp="#p_WWPWWKNB1">Prince Wan</persName> has
                    told him that certain Latin American countries are still in <pb facs="0600"
                        n="572" xml:id="pg_572"/> doubt as to whom they will support for the Ninth
                    General Assembly Presidency. The Ambassador stated that <persName
                        corresp="#p_WWPWWKNB1">Prince Wan</persName> had asked him to communicate
                    this to the Department and to inquire whether the Department would assist by
                    making representations to these certain Latin American countries.</p>
                <p>I stated that this is a matter which I would take up in the Department and would
                    let him know.</p>
                <p>The Ambassador also stated that <persName corresp="#p_WWPWWKNB1">Prince
                        Wan</persName> had suggested to the Dutch in New York a deal whereby
                        <persName corresp="#p_WWPWWKNB1">Wan</persName> would guarantee Latin
                    American support for <persName corresp="#p_KLEFFENSEN1">Van Kleffens</persName>
                    for the Presidency in 1955, and the Europeans and <persName
                        corresp="#p_WWPWWKNB1">Wan</persName> would guarantee the Presidency to the
                    Latin Americans in 1956, if <persName corresp="#p_KLEFFENSEN1">Van
                        Kleffens</persName> would withdraw this year. The Ambassador stated that the
                    Dutch did not react favorably to this idea.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WAINHOUSEDW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">David W. Wainhouse</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
